default This can be illustrated by a rough calculation considering infections solely in the 1941-85 cohort.  At the height of exposure to BSE, circa 1990, this cohort comprised about 30m people, 40% (12m) of them MM homozygotes.  A prevalence of 1 in 2,000 (if due to primary infection) implies that 6,000 of these individuals would have been infected through BSE exposure.  Collectively, they would have had life-expectancy normal for their age, so there would have been only a small number of deaths due to other causes.  Had the incubation periods seen in the actual MM cases been typical of this larger MM group, most of these 6,000 infections would already have appeared as clinical cases.  This takes no account of additional infections in other genotypes or in other age cohorts.
